# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- We are asked to divide the array into k sub-arrays
- the score is the sum of the beginning value and end value for all sub-arrays
- if k is the same as array length, there's only 1 way:
    - Each element is a subarray iself
    - In this case the score diff between max and min is 0
-  To divide an array into k sub-arrays means to find k-1 delimiters ("|" in below) within the array to divide the aray
    - [1,2|3,4|5,6]: two "|" divides the array into three sub arrays
    - each "|" will increase the total score by ```weights[i-1] + weights[i]```, say index before and after "|" is ```i-1``` and ```i```
- Now our goal is to find the largest k-1 "|" and the smallest k-1 "|", how?
    - create a new array of ```weights.length-1```, (you could re-use the same array, but for simplicity, we'll use a new one)
    - put the sum at each "|" (```weights[i-1] + weights[i]```) into new array
    - sort it
    - now you get the top ```k-1``` and smallest ```k-1``` sum, return the difference

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlogn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n) or O(1) if you reuse the same array
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```java
class Solution {
    public long putMarbles(int[] weights, int k) {
        int n = weights.length;
        if (k == n) return 0;
        int[] W = new int[n-1];
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) W[i-1] = weights[i] + weights[i-1];
        Arrays.sort(W);

        return max(W, k-1) - min(W, k-1);
    }

    private long max(int[] W, int k) {
        int n = W.length;
        long res = 0;
        for (int i = n-1; i >= n-k; i--) res += W[i];
        return res;
    }

    private long min(int[] W, int k) {
        long res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) res += W[i];
        return res;
    }
}
```
