solutions.content:
# Intuition
We can see that the last and first will be always added in both max and min evaluation and will get cancel out each other.
So now the question modified as, find out k-1 separation points in the given list so that there sum will be max and min.


# Approach
1. To achieve this we can simple need to track the top k-1 pairs whose sum is max and k-1 pirs whose sum is min.
To get this we can use minHeap and maxHeap to accumulate the values and at the end of evaluation of each pair take sum of each of the top k-1 values in both the heap and return the difference.

2. Second approach could be take another array which stores the sum of two consicutive values possible and simply sort it.
Then take the sum of largest k-1 elements and sum of smallest k-1 values and return ans as the diff of these two.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
We need to push at max k element to the heap: O(nlogk)

- Space complexity:
At max we need to store N elements, so its O(N)

# Code

1. Using heap solution:
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long putMarbles(vector<int>& weights, int k) {
        priority_queue<int> pqMin;
        priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> pqMax;
        for(int i = 1; i < weights.size(); ++i){
            pqMax.push(weights[i] + weights[i-1]);
            pqMin.push(weights[i] + weights[i-1]);
            if(pqMax.size() >= k) { pqMax.pop(); pqMin.pop(); }
        }
        long long ans = 0;
        while(pqMax.size() > 0){
            ans += pqMax.top() - pqMin.top();
            pqMax.pop(); pqMin.pop();
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

2. Using Sorting:
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long putMarbles(vector<int>& weights, int k) {
        long long ans = 0;
        vector<int> psum;
        for(int i = 1; i < weights.size(); ++i){ psum.push_back(weights[i] + weights[i-1]); }
        sort(psum.begin(), psum.end());
        for(int i = 0; i < k-1; i++ ){ ans += psum[psum.size() - 1 - i] - psum[i];  }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

