# Please Upvote 😇
---
It is been observed that, whenever we make a partition, and add the costs of the bags, we always get a pair sum like this:

*current bag's `j`th weight and next bag's `i`th weight*

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e1512b5a-1f11-4bca-9653-c30835a5042b_1674975455.079999.png)


So we can make as many partitions and we will always have `w[j] (current bag) + W[i] (next bag)` present in the score.

And our score is nothing but sum of all such pairs:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/deae3f9e-4541-4c97-a0b2-cb1507817adb_1674976428.7052581.png)


So every `w[k] + w[k + 1]` will be present in the score when we make all possible partitions.

So we will store `w[k] + w[k + 1]` in an array and sort it.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/06405b30-85bd-4b2d-b057-5422bd241477_1674976202.2843637.png)

So for `k` bags, number of partitions put will be `k - 1`.
We know sum of all costs gives us the score.
So we will run a loop on the array which stores our bag costs:
- The first `k - 1` cost sum will be our minimum possible score.
- The last `k - 1` cost sum will be our maximum possible score.

``` java []
class Solution {
    public long putMarbles(int[] weights, int k) {
        int n = weights.length;
        // if number of bags = number of marbles
        // minimum score = sum of cost of each bag/marble
        // maximum score = sum of cost of each bag/marble
        // so both are equal hence difference is 0
        if (k == n) {
            return 0;
        }

        int[] costs = new int[n-1];
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) { 
            costs[i] = weights[i] + weights[i+1];
        }

        Arrays.sort(costs);

        long min = 0, max = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < k - 1; i++) {
            min += costs[i];
            max += costs[n-i-2];    
            // length of costs is n-1 
            // so last index is n-1-1 = n-2
        }

        return max - min;
    }
}
```
### Time complexity: $$O(n) + O(n * logn) => O(n * logn)$$
### Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

