solutions.content:
The intuition for this problem could be tricky to see.

If we make a division after point `j`, it adds `w[j] + w[j + 1]` to the score.

We make `k - 1` divisions, and the total score includes weights of all division pairs, plus the weight of the first and last marble.

For the maximum/minimum score, we need to pick `k - 1` division pairs with the highest/lowest combined weight. 

## Sort
Easier, but not as efficient as nth element.

If `k` is greater than half of the array, min/max pairs will overlap. In that case, we only need to get `n - k` pairs.

**C++**
```cpp
long long putMarbles(vector<int>& w, int k) {
    if (k == 1 || k == w.size())
        return 0;
    vector<long long> gaps;
    transform(begin(w), prev(end(w)), begin(w) + 1, back_inserter(gaps), plus());    
    sort(begin(gaps), end(gaps));
    k = min(k, (int)w.size() - k + 1);
    return transform_reduce(rbegin(gaps), rbegin(gaps) + k - 1, begin(gaps), 0LL, plus(), minus());
}
```

## Nth Element
The runtime of this solution is ~50% better, since we do not need scores in a perfect order.

**C++**
```cpp
long long putMarbles(vector<int>& w, int k) {
    if (k == 1)
        return 0;    
    vector<long long> gaps;
    transform(begin(w), prev(end(w)), begin(w) + 1, back_inserter(gaps), plus());
    k = min(k, (int)w.size() - k + 1);
    nth_element(begin(gaps), begin(gaps) + k - 1, end(gaps));
    nth_element(begin(gaps) + k, begin(gaps) + gaps.size() - k, end(gaps));
    return transform_reduce(rbegin(gaps), rbegin(gaps) + k - 1, begin(gaps), 0LL, plus(), minus());
}
```

