solutions.content:
**Observations:**
-> We need to make exactly 'k' non-empty contiguous partitions of the array (arr).
-> The first partition starts at index 0 and last partitions ends at n-1, where n is the size of arr.
-> Any point at which one partition ends and the next partition starts from, let us call it 'pivot'
-> Thus there are 2*k total points that make n-1 pivots.
-> Thus there are k-1 pivots.
-> Each pivote is of the form (i, i+1).
-> The value of a pivot is arr[i]+arr[i+1]
-> Thus the overall max is arr[0]+ sum of scores of the k-1 highest valued pivots + arr[n-1]
-> Thus the overall min is arr[0]+ sum of scores of the k-1 smallest valued pivots + arr[n-1]
-> Final answer is max-min.
-> In general, how do we iterate over a sequence and find k of the n highest/smallest items?
-> The answer is piority_queue
```
class Solution {
public:
typedef long long ll;
long long putMarbles(vector<int>&v, int k) {
    priority_queue<ll>pqmx;
    priority_queue<ll,vector<ll>,greater<ll>>pqmn;
    ll n=v.size();
    for(ll i=0;i<n-1;++i){
        pqmx.push(v[i]+v[i+1]), pqmn.push(v[i]+v[i+1]);
        if(pqmx.size()>k-1){
            pqmx.pop(), pqmn.pop();
        }
    }
    ll ans=0;
    while(!pqmx.empty()){
        ans+=pqmn.top()-pqmx.top();
        pqmx.pop(), pqmn.pop();
    }
    return ans;
}
};
```

