# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The question is marked hard because many will not be able to get the intuition about the solution. If you see the first example,
`weights=[1,3,5,1];` we have to distribute the marbels such that we get max score and min score respectively. 
> Now if we see score for any distribution say [1,3 ||  5,1], ($$||$$ signifies partition), we can find the score as, (1+3)+(5+1)=10.

> Lets take some other distribution, say [1,3,5 || 1], we see the score is given by, (1+5)+(1+1)=8.

Now, if you notice `first element` and `last element` will always be present, but one thing which is worth noticing is that `the element at end of a partition and the start of another partition,` is always present in the score, which means consecutive elements which are present left and right at the partition wall are always present in the score. eg:-(3,5) in first example and (5,1) in second example.  

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Now to execute our intuition we would first take an array `pairs` and 
find the sum of every consecutive pairs,and `sort` it. 
> The first k-1 elements of the sorted array will correspond to the minimum score and last k-1 elments of the sum will correspond to the maximum score.k-1 due to the fact that the no of partition pairs will be one less than k(try counting).
To find all pair sum:-
```
int pairs[]= new int[weights.length-1];
        int index=0;
        for(int i=0,j=1;i<weights.length-1;i++,j++){
            pairs[index]=weights[i]+weights[j];
            index+=1;}
```
To find maximum and minimum score:-
```
long min=0,max=0;
        for(int i=0,j=pairs.length-1;i<k-1;i++,j--){
            min+=pairs[i];
            max+=pairs[j];
        }
```
# Complexity
- Time complexity:    O(nlogn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ --> 

- Space complexity:    O(n)
