# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem is really a hard nut to crack. It requires great obersvation skills and can be only understood, if we look at the examples properly. Let me try to explain with an example

**Let the array be [1,3,5,1,3,4] and k = 2**

Now what are the cases that are possible

The cases are as follows

**[1] + [3,5,1,3,4] = > (1+1) + (3+4) => 9**

**[1,3] + [5,1,3,4] => (1+3) + (5+4) => 13**

**[1,3,5] + [1,3,4] => (1+5) + (1+4) => 11**

**[1,3,5,1] + [3,4] => (1+1) + (3+4) => 9**

**[1,3,5,1,3] + [4] => (1+3) + (4+4) => 12**

Now, what can be observe in every case, 

**There are 2 numbers which come in every case,  that is index no 0 and index no last(5)**, **the no 1 and 4 are added in every sum**, it means however we do the partitions , **index no 0 and last index are always going to come in our sum**,

If they are coming again and again , **the question arises do we need to take them** , because if we see 

Our question says that we need to do **max-min** , but this 1 and 4 will be present in max and as well as min

so it means that if we don't include this 1 and 4 **there wont be an affect on our ans** 

Now the question arises , **how do we find the sum of other pairs**

For that we need some **cute observation** 

Let us take the above example only 

Let us do the partition like this => 

[1,3] + [5,1,3,4] => Here, the sum is (1+3) and (5+4 ) but as i said above 1 and 4 are not important so we can remove that so the remaining numbers are 3 and 5 , which is 8

Now , we can see a **pattern** here 

The pattern is, if we take them sum from (**weight[zero index] + weights[some i]) + (weight[i+1]+weight[last_index])** we see that we only need to do the sum of **(weight[i]+weight[i+1])**, 

You can see in the above case also, we did a sum of 3+5 **which is i and i+1**

So how do we find all the pairs now, it is simple 

Just make an array say partition and insert the sum of **weight[i]+weight[i+1] for every index** , This is the sum of every pair presnt in the array 

so for the above example that is [1,3,5,1,3,4] , the partition array will be [4,8,6,4,7]

***Partition array is the sum of every pair present in the array (THIS IS THE CRUX OF THE QUESTION)***,

Now how do we get the max and min , the ans is simple 

**sort the array and just subtract the smallest element from the biggest element**

Now, here i took an example where k was 2, so we could have only 1 partition so that is why we subtacted the smallest element from the max element in the partition array

If k==3, then what changes we will make 

If k is 3, it means we require 2 pairs , and we have the list of sum of all pairs 

partition  = [4,8,6,4,7] which after sorting becomes [4,4,6,7,8], so **now we just need to (7+8)-(4+4)** because we require 2 pairs , so **max will have 2 pairs and min will have 2 pairs** 

This is how we solve these type of questions

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1) Make a vector named partition which will have sum of all the pairs

2) Run your loop for n-1 times as we if we have n elements then we will have n-1 pairs and for every index just store weight[i]+weight[i+1]

3) Now just sort your partion array and find the sum of first k-1 elemtts in the partition array to get the minimum sum and find the sum of last k-1 elemets to get the max sum

4) Subtract both of them and return your ans :)
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are sorting the array so **O(N*LOGN)**

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are making a partition array so **O(N)**

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long putMarbles(vector<int>& weights, int k) {

        vector<long long int>pq;

        for(int i=0; i<weights.size()-1; i++)
        {
            long long int a = weights[i]+weights[i+1];
            pq.push_back(a);
        }

        sort(pq.begin(),pq.end());

        long long int a = 0;

        for(int i=0; i<k; i++)
        {
            a+=pq[i];
        }
        long long int b = 0;
        int i = pq.size()-1;

        while(k>0)
        {
            b+=pq[i];
            i--;
            k--;
        }
        long long int ans ;
        ans  = b-a;
        return ans;
    }
};
```

