# Intuition
We can represent the bags as a list of indexes, where each index is the position where the last bag starts, and the next one ends. This works because it is not permitted to have any unused marbles - therefore, there will be no gaps between bags. 

Once we consider it thustly, we just need to find the best values for these indexes - without any requirement that we find them in order.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We build an array of 'pairs' - where a pair is the sum of a weight and the weight that comes after it. Because we don't need to find the pairs in any specific order, we can just sort the list of pairs and pick the leading and trailing k-1 values, and take the difference between the sums.


```text
a is the start of a bag, b is the end of a bag. 
Any (b) is an index that we've chosen.

k=3, [50, 51, 30, 1, 9, 9, 1]
--------------------------------
a              (b)  a   (b)   ab  79  <- smallest
50   51   30   1    9    9    1 
a(b) a(b) a                   b  233 <- largest
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n*log(n))$$ - the time it takes to sort the pairs.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$ - could also be done in $$O(1)$$ by reusing the input array.

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} weights
 * @param {number} k
