# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. `int n = weights.size()`;: This line initializes an integer variable `n` with the size of the `weights` vector, which represents the number of marbles.

2. `vector<int> temp`;: This creates an empty vector temp to store the sums of adjacent marble weights.

3. `for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++)`: This loop iterates over the weights vector up to the second-to-last element (index n-1) because the last element does not have a next element to add with.

4. Inside the loop, `temp.push_back(weights[i] + weights[i+1])`; calculates the sum of the current marble weight (`weights[i]`) and the next marble weight (`weights[i+1]`), and adds it to the temp vector.

5. `sort(temp.begin(), temp.end())`;: This sorts the temp vector in ascending order. Now, temp contains the sums of adjacent marble weights in non-decreasing order.

6. `long long miniSum = 0, maxiSum = 0`;: These variables are initialized to 0 to store the minimum and maximum sums of adjacent marble weights.

7. `for (int i = 0; i < k-1; i++)`: This loop iterates k-1 times, where k represents the number of marbles to be put. It calculates the minimum and maximum sums of adjacent marble weights by considering the first k-1 elements of the sorted temp vector and the last k-1 elements in reverse order.

8. Inside the loop, `miniSum += temp[i]`; adds the i-th element of temp to the miniSum.

9. `maxiSum += temp[n-2-i]`; adds the n-2-i-th element of temp to the maxiSum, which represents the reverse order.

10. Finally, return `maxiSum - miniSum`; calculates the difference between the maximum and minimum sums of adjacent marble weights and returns it as the result of the putMarbles function.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n⋅log⁡n)$$
