# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
When diving stones in k bags, basically we need k subarrays and for k subarrays we need to consider the points where the array is partitioned into subarray.
e.g.

[1,3,5] => [1|3,5]

So, in above example we need to consider the elements before and after the partition(i.e. 1 and 3).

Hence, we can store the sum of all such partitions in PrioritityQueues (minHeap and maxHeap)

Get k elements from both PriorityQueues and difference of sum of these k-1 elements will be the result.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(nlogn)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public long PutMarbles(int[] weights, int k) {
        PriorityQueue<int, int> max = new PriorityQueue<int, int>();
        PriorityQueue<int, int> min = new PriorityQueue<int, int>();

        for(int i=0; i<weights.Length-1; i++){
            int sum = weights[i] + weights[i+1];
            max.Enqueue(sum, -sum);
            min.Enqueue(sum, sum);
        }

        long maxSum = 0;
        long minSum = 0;

        for(int i=0; i<k-1; i++){
            maxSum += max.Dequeue();
            minSum += min.Dequeue();
        }

        return maxSum - minSum;
    }
}
```

