solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To solve this problem optimally, I have used **Greedy approach**. 
We could use **Dynamic Programming** also, as **we have to divide the array into k subarrays**. We need to put (k-1)partitions in (n-1) locations. While placing a partition we have always the option of placing it after a index (let's say idx) or we can also place it after idx+1. 
So we have two chose between options which we use in DP. If we are given n and k, then we need to place k-1 partitions in n-1 locations.
But this approach will have the time complexity of **(n-1)C(k-1)** which is exponential.
**So the Greedy approach seems better** to think about right now.
- If we read the problem, we understand that I should be only concerned with the maximum and minimum sum.
- And  the sums are the summation of the k pairs which consists of the first and last elements of each k subarray.
***If the array input is :-***
a   b   c   d   e   f   g
and k = 3.
And if i just randomly partition it in following way:-
a   b   |   c   d   e   |   f   g
The summation will be (a+b) + (c+e) + (f+g)
**You can partition it in any way and you will oberve few points such as -** 
- The sum always consists of the last and first element of array.
- The remaining elements (in the sum) are in pairs of adjacent elements such as (b,c),(e,f).


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- So why don't we just find out the summation of all the adjacent element pairs and push them into a new vector. And then we can just sort the **new vector** and find the summation of the **smallest and biggest k-1 pairs**.
- If array is a,b,c,d,e,f,g. Push (a+b,b+c,c+d,e+f,f+g) and sort the vector. 
- And our answer will be the difference between the biggest k-1 pairs summation and smallest k-1 pairs summation solution.

# Complexity
Let n be the length of the weights array.

Sorting the "new" vector takes O(nlogn) time complexity.
The iteration to calculate the minimum and maximum scores takes O(k) time complexity.
Thus, the overall time complexity of the solution is O(nlogn).
The space complexity is O(n) to store the "new" vector.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long putMarbles(vector<int>& weights, int k) {
        int n = weights.size();
        vector<int> pairs;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++)
            pairs.push_back(weights[i] + weights[i+1]);
        sort(pairs.begin(), pairs.end());
        long long mini = 0, maxi = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < k-1; i++){
            mini += pairs[i];
            maxi += pairs[n-2-i];
        }
        return maxi - mini;
    }
};
```

