Suppose we have a sequence: `a,....x,y,...,b` and plan to cut between `x` and `y`, we define this cut's value is `x + y` because `new_sum = old_sum + x + y`.

Then we can use priority queue to catch `big cut` for maximum result and `small cut` for mimimum result.
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn put_marbles(weights: Vec<i32>, k: i32) -> i64 {
        use std::collections::BinaryHeap;
        use std::cmp::Reverse;

        let mut a = BinaryHeap::with_capacity(weights.len() - 1);
        let mut b = BinaryHeap::with_capacity(weights.len() - 1);

        for i in 1..weights.len() {
            a.push(weights[i] + weights[i - 1]);
            b.push(Reverse(weights[i] + weights[i - 1]));
        }

        let mut min = (weights[0] + weights[weights.len() - 1]) as i64;
        let mut max = min;

        for _ in 1..k {
            max += a.pop().unwrap() as i64;
            min += b.pop().unwrap().0 as i64;
        }
        max - min
    }
}
```

