# Intuition
Let's go with the natural intution of having to form k-1 boundaries and then taking the sum of first and last element of each subarray enclosed within two consecutive boundaries.
But there are a lot of ways to arrange those boundaries and hence the subarrays enclosed.
Let's make the implementation easier with the following observation:
Suppose weights array is
`1 2 3 11 4 6 7` and `k = 2`

and say you insert boundary like this
`1 2 3 | 11 4 6 7`

Now when you move on to find max_score (say) you do
`wt[0] + wt[boundary_pos-1] + wt[boundary_pos+1] + wt[n-1]`

You won't be inserting the boundaries practically so, -1 and +1 in indices need to be adjusted accordingly

# Approach

Now that you know that only the elements to the left and right of a boundary matter, you can simply form an array of size n-1 which has sum of all adjacent pairs.

then,
max_score= `a[0] + a[len-1] + summation of largest k-1 values from a`,
min_score= `a[0] + a[len-1] + summation of smallest k-1 values from a`
then when you take difference the first and last elements lose their role thus it just **boils down to (largest k-1 - smallest k-1) adjacent pair sums**

Wohoo! we're done with the thought process and build-up part, now what's remaining is to code it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlogn)

- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
#define ll long long
class Solution {
public:
    long long putMarbles(vector<int>& wt, int k) {

        //form boundaries instead of forming partitions
        //find top k-1 elements from all x, x+1s i.e. to say boundary exists b/w x & x+1

        int n=wt.size();
        vector<ll> a;

        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){
            a.push_back(wt[i-1]+wt[i]);
        }

        //max_score=f+l+ largest k-1 in [1,n-2]
        //min_score=f+l+ smallest k-1 in [1,n-2]

        k-=1;
        sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        ll min_score=0, max_score=0;
        n=a.size();

        for(int i=0;i<k;i++)min_score+=a[i];
        for(int i=n-k;i<n;i++)max_score+=a[i];

        return max_score-min_score;      

    }
};
```

